Description

1995 Upper Deck is a 495-card set released in two series of 225 cards supplemented by a 45-card "Traded" set available exclusively via redemption cards. Each 12-card pack contained either an Electric Diamond parallel (retail) or a Special Edition insert (Hobby).

Randomly inserted into all Series Two packs are five different "Traded" redemption cards, each good for nine cards.

Distribution

Hobby/Retail: 36 packs per box, 12 cards per pack (MSRP: $1.99).

Predictors

Randomly inserted into packs this 100-card set features 19 players and one "Long Shot" in five categories: MVP, Rookie of the Year, Batting Average, Home Runs, and RBI. If the player depicted won the respective award/category, the card could then be redeemed for a special holographic-foil enhanced set of all the Predictor cards in that particular series. Collectors had until December 31, 1995 to redeem any winning Predictors. Winning cards are marked with a "W" in the checklist.

Award Winners

This set is exclusive to Hobby packs. Cards H1-H20 were in Series One Hobby packs while H21-H40 were in Series Two.

Winning card #H10 was good for a Predictor Award Winner Exchange set of cards #H1-H20. Cards #H38 and #40 were good for upgraded cards #H21-H40.

League Leaders

This set is exclusive to retail packs. Cards R1-R30 were in Series One retail packs while R31-R60 were in Series Two.

Winning cards #R1, R10, R11, R20, R27 and R30 were all good for a Predictor League Leader Exchange set of cards #R1-R30. Card #R49 was the only winning Predictor card inserted into Series Two retail packs and was good for set #R31-R60. Because there was only one winning Series Two card, the Series Two Predictor League Leader Exchange set is considered by some collectors to be one of the scarcest insert sets of the early 1990s.

Jumbo Autograph

These two over-sized (8" X 10") autographed cards were available exclusively through a wrapper redemption offer. Collectors who sent in 35 Series One (Clemens) or Series Two (A-Rod) Hobby wrappers and $5 for shipping and handling would get an autograph.

Each player signed only 8000 cards.
